              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f : \operatorname {Spec} E \to  \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/schm-0B23/" title="Quasi-separated and separated morphisms" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-0B23/" display-uri="schm-0B23" type="local">separated</fr:link> map between <fr:link href="/schm-IFX1/" title="Affine scheme" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-IFX1/" display-uri="schm-IFX1" type="local">affine schemes</fr:link>. Then by <fr:link href="/schm-FHDX/" title="Separated morphisms between affine schemes" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-FHDX/" display-uri="schm-FHDX" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-FHDX/" display-uri="schm-FHDX" /></fr:link>, for any <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \operatorname {Spec} D]]></fr:tex> the fibre <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f^{-1}(x)]]></fr:tex> in particular is <html:em>discrete</html:em>. Since the fibre as a <fr:link href="/schm-S9SD/" title="Fibre products of schemes are topological" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-S9SD/" display-uri="schm-S9SD" type="local">pullback</fr:link> between affine schemes is affine, having a discrete specialisation relation implies it is a <html:em>Stone space</html:em>.
</html:p>
                <html:p>
  However, this is <html:em>not</html:em> a sufficient condition. See <fr:link href="/schm-C8GC/" title="Separated and non-separated maps between affine schemes" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-C8GC/" display-uri="schm-C8GC" type="local">Example <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-C8GC/" display-uri="schm-C8GC" /></fr:link>.
</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
