            <fr:title text="Relative Booleanisation of relative Boolean algebra is Boolean">Relative Booleanisation of relative Boolean algebra is Boolean</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>
  Combining <fr:link href="/idem-comm-E8MW/" title="Relative Boolean algebras are stable under base change" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-E8MW/" display-uri="idem-comm-E8MW" type="local">Remark <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-E8MW/" display-uri="idem-comm-E8MW" /></fr:link> and <fr:link href="/idem-comm-22W2/" title="Relative Boolean algebras over a Boolean base are simply Boolean algebras" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-22W2/" display-uri="idem-comm-22W2" type="local">Lemma <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-22W2/" display-uri="idem-comm-22W2" /></fr:link>, it follows that if we have a <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>-Boolean algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \to  E]]></fr:tex>, then the pushout along the Booleanisation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \to  \lambda  D]]></fr:tex>
  
  <html:figure><fr:resource hash="ecf5497f6ca8849911cdf2943bcba5ed"><fr:resource-content><html:img src="/ecf5497f6ca8849911cdf2943bcba5ed.svg" /></fr:resource-content><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="preamble"><![CDATA[\usepackage {tikz-cd}\usepackage {quiver}]]></fr:resource-source><fr:resource-source type="latex" part="body"><![CDATA[
    \begin {tikzcd}
      D & E \\
      {\lambda  D} & {\lambda _DE}
      \arrow [from=1-1, to=1-2]
      \arrow [from=1-1, to=2-1]
      \arrow [from=1-2, to=2-2]
      \arrow [from=2-1, to=2-2]
      \arrow ["\lrcorner "{anchor=center, pos=0.125, rotate=180}, draw=none, from=2-2, to=1-1]
    \end {tikzcd}
  ]]></fr:resource-source></fr:resource></html:figure>

  makes <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lambda _DE]]></fr:tex> a Boolean algebra. This in particular says that for a relative Boolean algebra <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D \to  E]]></fr:tex>, if we universally add all complements coming from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>, then we get a Boolean algebra. Hence, in this sense the only missing Boolean negations are the ones from <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex>. However, this is <html:em>not</html:em> a sufficient condition for being a relative Boolean algebra: see <fr:link href="/idem-comm-NIFX/" title="Relative Booleanisation is Boolean iff it has Stone fibres" uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-NIFX/" display-uri="idem-comm-NIFX" type="local">Proposition <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/idem-comm-NIFX/" display-uri="idem-comm-NIFX" /></fr:link> and <fr:link href="/schm-IGER/" title="Separated maps between affine schemes have Stone fibres" uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-IGER/" display-uri="schm-IGER" type="local">Remark <fr:contextual-number uri="https://charloced.github.io/schm-IGER/" display-uri="schm-IGER" /></fr:link>.
</html:p>
